<p>When selecting a solar installer in Charlotte, prioritize companies with North Carolina electrical contractor licenses and NABCEP (North American Board of Certified Energy Practitioners) certifications. Look for installers with specific experience working with Duke Energy's interconnection requirements and local permitting processes in Mecklenburg County. Quality installers should offer comprehensive warranties covering equipment (typically 20-25 years for panels, 10-15 years for inverters) and workmanship (minimum 5-10 years). Request multiple quotes, verify insurance coverage, check Better Business Bureau ratings, and ask for local references from recent Charlotte installations. Reputable companies will provide detailed system performance estimates, handle all permitting and utility interconnection paperwork, and offer monitoring systems to track your solar production.</p>

